The mass slaughter of staff
The new book by Peter Englund depth and generosity. "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War" (The beauty and grief: A History of the First World War), it begins with a long list of characters who you heart.
A Board to begin: tape carefully this page and make your bookmark.
You'll learn about these people in detail. In this romantic story of Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon in those few moments where, as one of his men or women, you will be disturbed and desperate in the fog of war.
Peter Englund is a historian and journalist Swedish.
It is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which issues the Nobel Prize for literature.
He has written a book of which he described, accurately, as "a work of anti-histoire."
It contains a few names, the major treaties or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion on strategies and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, "he explains," that a "book describing what it was like." There are "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"The beauty and grief" summarizes the experiences in war of 20 men and women more or less ordinary, on both sides of the war, of young schoolgirls and botanists to stair climbing machines, doctors, ambulance and sellers.
Some will become heroes.
Other prisoners of war. Will lose some of its members, will become crazy or will lose their lives.
Their lives are here as the candles of a church: while some off, and new ones.
The book by Peter Englund departs from the history books.
Perhaps some statement to the idea that the First World War is that by the terrible trench warfare on the Western Front.
"The beauty and grief" describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, the Mesopotamia and the East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; one spent Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are a problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
The war invades the lives of these people such as a natural disaster, such a hurricane Katrina, which the cordite.
When its cannon ringing in the distance, and you are a mother at home, or are you staying fuyez-vous?
That will come anyway?
Almost nobody can understand what happened, or even the reasons for the war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been expanded by assumptions, expectations, fears, ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours."
"The beauty and grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, a nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young Marine German ports.
Their stories are drawn primarily from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying and exciting, but are more preserved through the accumulation of small moments and details.
Most address the deprivation and the ability to cope.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund wrote: "apex, ersatz everywhere."
"Coffee, false imitation of aluminum, rubber, paper, wood."
It builds on the food replacement in Germany.
It describes the "meat made of rice cooked in fat mutton (and finished with a false bones of wood); manufactured tobacco with root dry and dried skin potato; the amount of wood."
He says that "837 meat permitted substitute are registered in the production of sausages and 511 cafés substitution."
Some stories address the honour and courage.
An American recognizes its own drive to the savagery and declared the war: "You feel that, after all, this is what the men were targeted, rather than sitting in a comfortable chair, a cigarette and a whisky in the hand, reading a newspaper or a bestseller, and instead of pretending that such a polish is synonymous with civilization, and that there is no formal barbaric behind your shirt and ultra-greasy.
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that it is likely to die, and that no one will notice or pay attention.
"When you is resigned to sacrifice, we hope to have a public."
It is unfortunately rather comparable to "a condemned man strangled in secret."
Other comments related to the decline of an old Europe and new types of terror.
"The conflict is increasingly becoming a history of economic competition" wrote Peter Englund, "a war between the plants."
It captures the arrival of what he calls "a new species within the bestiary at the beginning of the century: the mass murderer well articulated and convinced ideologically, clothing well pruned, which carries out its beef while sitting behind a desk."
People act in unexpected ways; there were as many core behaviours that heroism.
