The union of school aid continues the city for redundancies
The union representing hundreds of aid school who lost their jobs last month plans to initiate a trial Wednesday to the city to unnecessary redundancies and discriminatory. The impact is disproportionate on schools serving disadvantaged pupils.
Prosecutions are probably the ultimate weapon of the union, Council of the 37th District, in an attempt to put a stop to layoffs.
Six hundred and seventy-two aid coordinators of school, parents and other employees, part of the paid less of the city, have lost their jobs on October 7. The union leaders have compared these redundancies to a political vendetta that she did not allow the city to a fund for health care led by groups of workers, and that would have to close the budget gap last spring.
Municipal authorities have denied the accusation.
At a hearing before the City Council last month, Chancellor Dennis M. Walcott said that the redundancies were part of the budget closed in June.
A member of the Council responded, saying that the layoffs of school aid n "were not specified in the budget.
The officers of the Council of the 37th District said they would fulfil a notice of claim, warning the Education Department that it would be pursued; a press conference will be held on Wednesday to officially announce the prosecution to the State Supreme Court in Manhattan.
Dennis M. Walcott and the department of education of the city will be the defendant. The complainants will be represented by eight workers made redundant, all black in colour or origin Latin American, as most of the aid school who have lost their jobs.
Elizabeth Thomas, spokesman of the legal department of the city, said that the municipality has still not been able to see the reasons for the trial and therefore cannot comment on the allegations.
According to a draft of complaints obtained by the New York Times, the union based on the number of redundancies in schools in the most deprived areas of the city to support its complaint against unfair treatment, saying that schools the poorest would lose the most aid due to underfunding.
While there are no dismissal on Staten Island, and a few sentences in the Upper East Side or TriBeCa, 17 school aides lost their jobs in the 23th District of Brownsville, and 46 in the 8th and 9th Districts southern districts in the Bronx.
Noting the loss of five school aid on eight employed at Public School 36 in Harlem, where 68% of school children live in poverty, the prosecution say that "This is not a district of affluent parents who can get funds to make up the difference."
The budget of the Public School 36 has been reduced by 3.26% this year. Funds have also been lost when the city has changed its calculation of supplemental funding for each entry "student.
The union also says that the directors of schools have been misled by certain terms in a memo authorizing the dismissal of coordinators of the parents.
The memo employed the term "overshoot" to describe the action, even if "overshoot" described more generally to the action of moving a teacher in a school to a group of available workers whose salaries are paid by the central office.
According to the complaints, "Sixty-six coordinators of parents have been laid off," and "not only because they have exceeded."
Mission: Congress reaches an agreement on the issue of Libya
It would appear that the Republicans and the Democrats have reached an agreement on Capitol Hill on the question of the uprising in Libya.
It took an uprising succeeded, the capture and death of longtime dictator Muammar Gaddafi as well as the American involvement.
The Senate Foreign Relations Committee will have to take a decision next Tuesday, supported by President John Kerry (Democrat - Massachusetts), with Senators John McCain (Republican - Arizona) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Independent, Connecticut), applauding the Libyan people for their revolt and American troops for their "courage."
"This resolution is to honour the courage of the Libyans as they begin to rebuild their country," said John Kerry.
"This is a bipartisan support to their democratic aspirations."
The language may be harmless but the debate on the Libya has never been simple to date.
This summer, legislators of both parties came into conflict, as well as with the White House, on the formulation of several resolutions to approve or not the role of the United States military in the NATO mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain introduced a resolution to authorize the limited use of American military forces in Libya.
The bill was defeated by a large bipartisan margin and has never been the subject of a vote in the Senate.
But the same day of the failure of the bill, the Chamber of Deputies has also rejected a measure to reduce the funding of U.S. operations in Libya.
The American mission is therefore remained under a form of purgatory - the legislative Congress upset enough to criticise the management of the mission by Obama, but not enough to pull the rug from underneath the foot.
The indecision of the Congress has been overtaken by events.
Tripoli has fallen under the insurgents in August and Gaddafi was killed on October 20.
The NATO mission officially ended on 31 October.
The Senate can now act.
The resolution of the Foreign Relations Committee "congratulates the Libyan people for their courage and determination in view of freedom" and "congratulate the men and women of American armed forces and their coalition partners involved in military operations to protect the Libyan people, for their courage and professionalism."
The resolution also says "the national interest of the United States to reach an irreversible and successful transition to democracy in Libya."
The new measure good all the support of the Foreign Affairs Committee of the Senate or divisera-t-elle legislators as last June?
Senator and President of the Commission D. Richard Lugar (Independent) objected to the latest version.
His spokesman said on Monday that Richard D. Lugar had not yet read the latest version of new project.
In the Capitol, the House must vote this week an amendment to the Constitution to obtain a balanced budget, a legislative priority for almost all of the Congress, Republicans and some Democrats.
The measure, supported by the Republican Bob Goodlatte (Virginia), will be the first constitutional amendment on the budget, or any other issue, to obtain a floor vote in the House or the Senate.
Other legislators have not managed to get their amendments but it is not without trying.
The amendment of Goodlatte is part of the 68 constitutional amendments have been introduced in Congress, on a wide range of subjects.
Some are recurrent - the same bill proposed in both the House and the Senate - and others are slight variations of a precedent.
There are at least 15 versions in the House of the only amendment for a balanced budget, and another handful who "control federal spending."
Some of these bills are identical, but give their support - including the new Republicans who want to gild their CV - the chance to boast of being "the author" of such a measure.
The law on the control of the budget (Budget Control Act) approved last August was the vote of the House and the Senate on the amendment of a balanced budget.
In March, 58 senators voted in favour of a non-binding resolution supporting the idea of such an amendment.
Beyond the budget, several members wish to limit the number of mandates during which members of Congress can be used, while José E. Serrano (Democrat - New York) wants to lift the two-term limit for presidents.
Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Democrat - Illinois) proposed a multitude of amendments guaranteeing the right to quality education and health care, among others.
An amendment prohibiting marriage between individuals of the same sex is perennially proposed, as the amendment prohibiting the desecration of the flag.
Some lawmakers also want to authorize the cancellation of federal laws if two-thirds of the States are opposed.
Also eager that have been members to offer amendments, they are not as rapid as in the past.
At the 111th Congress, legislators have proposed 77 amendments, and 66 at the 110 th.
The pace slows in the early 1990 s, when the members were generally more than 150 amendments every two years, according to figures provided by the Library of the Senate.
But these amendments were not much more successful than they are today.
The last amendment to have been added - the 27th - was ratified in 1992 but proposed to Congress in 1789.
