I am sure that the organisers had good intentions.
I know.
But this was not just respect. The pity.
The conflicting impressions absolutely illustrate the difficult relationships which arose between the military and an U.S. public passionate but often distant.
Praise was lavished on the troops for their sacrifices.
But they have a certain price, say some.
The public increasingly acts as if he was sorry for the men and women in uniform.
"We are not at all of the victims," said Brigadier General B. Sean MacFarland, who led the troops in Iraq and will soon be heading to Afghanistan.
"But it would appear that the only way we support is to lock ourselves in the role of spirits unlucky."
It is a very sensitive issue for the military leaders, who do not wish to appear not grateful or disagree with the public they serve.
They also realize that the anger of returners troops of the Vietnam War was much worse.
Thus, most of the conversations on the mercy are held in confidence among veterans.
After the return of his two sons of combat with the Marines, retired Colonel Mark Cancian has warned that the public would consider their service from two perspectives.
Some would be with respect as they have been confronted with insurgents and travelled to remote locations.
Others may be asking if "a veteran angry and violent beneath the surface," says Cancian, who fought in Iraq and returned to work on the Government to Washington.
When he was looking for a job, he said, he felt that a few people that made him the interviews were subtle if he would be able to cope with the stress of a strenuous job in Washington immediately after his return from combat.
"When you raise the subject of the service, you are faced with negative impressions," Colonel Cancian when he speaks to his son.
The difficulties of military arise, in part, from the American indifference to the wars.
The victories are rarely pleased by a country unfamiliar with the army and who sees little direct benefits of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.
"As a nation, we value more heroism in the same way as for the Second World War," says retired Lieutenant General David Extrajudicial, who led the troops in Afghanistan.
Instead, the congratulations of politicians and the people focus heavily on the depth of suffering.
The troops are known for the number of services, the number of friends lost or the extent of the injuries.
