This week, a hearing will decide whether Capital 28 men and women will go on trial against the army for a China on rape.
If so, hundreds of complainants will prepare the next.
The soldier of 1st Class Elizabeth Lyman was aged 25 and 11 weeks pregnant, the night she was raped by a soldier.
C "was in October 2008. It returned to its barracks to Miramar Air Station, north of San Diego, after having dinner with a friend, when she met with a colleague carrying a pack of beer.
He asked if he could join in his bedroom to drink a glass.
"C" was a wake-up call, "says Elizabeth Lyman.
But the Texane has set aside its concern.
I thought: no, it was 19 years ago.
"It is Texas," she says.
"I will have to follow my intuition."
A few minutes after entering the Chamber of Elizabeth Lyman, the man was caught from behind, by land and raped, she claimed.
This week, on 18 November, Elizabeth Lyman and 27 other members, some still in service and other not, will wait with anxiety the court decision in a landmark trial to be held in Arlington, Virginia, and who will decide whether a trial brought against the former Secretary of Defense Robert Gates and his predecessor, Donald Rumsfeld, will take place.
They are accused of not have halted the spread of rape within the army, undercutting the constitutional rights of soldiers.
Classified in February by Susan Burke, a lawyer in Washington, the trial involved 17 complainants. This number grew to 28 months - 25 women and 3 men, all claiming to have been violated or sexually abused by fellow soldiers. They also claim that the army has not investigated, prosecuted or provided adequate justice after the alleged attacks.
Susan Burke says the military galonnées, because the problem begins with them.
"The army is a vertical structure," she says.
"Who are individuals in a position to" eradicate the culture of retaliation? Leaders. "
Counsel also states that since February, she was contacted by almost 400 other survivors, most of which could be part of future legal proceedings.
Its strategy: instead of gathering all the complainants in this case - putting all your eggs in one basket - it will initiate several trial, if necessary, to maintain the pressure.
The defence team, for the Department of Defense, led by the American lawyer Neil MacBride, filed a motion to dismiss the case.
The court documents, obtained by Newsweek, detail the strategy of the defence, and essentially the fact that the army cannot be pursued by soldiers in service or not for injury caused in the armed forces.
In a 1950 decision of the Supreme Court, called the Feres Doctrine, the federal government is not responsible for injuries sustained by personnel on active service.
"The alleged evil is inherent in the military service of complainants" indicate the documents.
The Department of Defence refused to make any comment.
Things have changed since the 50 s.
While women have still not, officially, the right to go into combat, this distinction has only on paper: the front lines of the recent wars are rarely only male.
In Iraq as in Afghanistan, the teams of soldiers women play an increasingly important role, particularly in contact with the local women.
Result: on the two wars, 150 women soldiers lost their lives - two thirds in combat situations.
It is time for the army to modernize says Susan Burke.
It is not alone in this fight: three other trials are underway in addition to his own.
In the Yale Law School, the centre of veterans is preparing a case against the four main military academies for allegedly encouraging a misogynist.
On the other hand, the non-profit foundation Vietnam Veterans of America is preparing a lawsuit against the army, by focusing on the diagnosis of "personality disorders" awarded to victims of rape to give them leave - a relatively ordinary, according to activists such as Anu Bhagwaru Service Women's Action Network (action network of women military), a group for human rights.
His group filed a lawsuit in December to the Veterans Administration, blaming them for discriminatory practices in the way of dealing with requests for benefits for persons have been victims of sexual assault in the service.
Nine bills independent of each other have been submitted to Congress by a mixture of bipartisan senators and representatives, proposing various solutions.
In 2010, 3.158 sexual assaults were recorded in the centre of intervention and prevention of sexual assault (Sexual Assault Prevention and Response Office) the Department of Defence.
But it is well known that the number of sexual assault is underestimated. Indeed, according to the Pentagon's own estimate, this figure represents about 13.5% of the 19.000 incidents that year.
The report released in March is also studying the percentage of lawsuits: in 2010, 20% of cases in the army have been the subject of a trial - half the percentage of the civil justice system.
The complainants "case of Susan Burke describe their aggression as the first in a series of injuries.
In the case of Lyman, she informed the Military Police of rape less than a hour after the fact.
That night, she says, she was asked to tell 11 times in detail his rape at different police, doctors and commanders.
It has suffered a "rape kit" (literally a kit of rape), and the blood of her assailant - due to a cut to his arm - was found in his bed.
Six months later, in April 2009, Elizabeth Lyman is sitting before a judge, a trial in which it raised questions about his sexual relationship with her boyfriend earlier on the day of his aggression.
Six witnesses testified as witnesses of moral character for the perpetrator of the crime, which was eventually acquitted.
"I remember the day the verdict was reached," says Elizabeth Lyman.
"I thought I was going to begin to have contractions. I started yelling at the court."
"I was placed in a psychiatric unit, and when I exit, I remember saying to my commander" This was not his trial but my own. ""
Elizabeth Lyman was forced to see a military psychiatrist, which eventually diagnose a personality disorder, making it unfit for service.
In January 2010, she was dismissed in terms of less than honourable, to receive any benefit.
Does the case Lyman and other complainants proceed or not, that is a long history, "says John Turley, a law professor at the Faculty of Law of the University of Washington.
However, he noted, "In my opinion, they should be able to move forward."
Only this doctrine criticised since its introduction comes between them and a verdict.
I have always criticised the doctrine Feres.
The army is decades behind because it does not have the same benefits and deterrence posed by the responsibility.
"The odds are heavily against them... But it is important that they try," he said.
These things change only when the right have the will to fight.
If the trial is not in their favour, Susan Burke, counsel for the complainants, will bring together hundreds of other complainants to other trial.
"We will continue to fight against the army on this issue as long as there is no reform."
