The walls have eyes: researchers are studying you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the extreme right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was a simple guy with his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having been taken of a murderous madness in Norway in July, leaving 77 victims, has faced its first trial.
While Breivik acted alone, he was far from the be in cyberspace: he had spent much of the time before the attack on his computer, to discuss with a few millions of nationalist who support the far-right groups on social networking sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy... Support to Facebook.
"We have realized that he was not that hard to find," said Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by the Reflection Group thinktank on the digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is so full of personal information, "said Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the promotional tool of the site to find the people they seek with scientific precision - the way marketers have for years.
L "team of Jamie Bartlett has discovered that half a million members are fans extreme right-wing groups in Europe. It has targeted with advertisements, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, announcements invited users to respond to an inquiry. Questions raised their level of education, their attitudes towards violence and their optimism about their own future.
By coming into contact with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues interviewed 10.000 followers of 14 parties of the extreme right in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
"It is a new way of doing research," said Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not at all surprising: supporters online groups are rather men, young and against immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who associate activism online and offline are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screen."
L "study DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook has become the new essential tool in the hands of scientists.
The focus groups, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all the issues that affect the health issues such as social trends, thanks to the "I love," publications on the walls and restated articles.
With more than 800 million active users who add content on average three per day, the "supernova data" generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research that the site's name appears in the title of almost 800% over the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study of the people that you could not approach in the street.
"Before, when you were to conduct investigations on members of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You had to go to the party, but you would have never allowed to enter," said Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information."
Others say that the site could provide a means to identify and treat the health and social problems.
According to a recent study of D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and colleagues, young students who spoke of their exploits on Facebook while intoxicated had significantly more likely to be alcoholics that students quiet about them.
Megan Moreno suggests that the Members of students, such as consultants, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student whose status would speak too often of alcohol.
"You can't deal with a problem if you do not diagnosed," Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and Director of the Centre for the health, behaviour and development of children to the Research Institute for Children located in Seattle, says the Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and that would in another case not recognized."
Facebook also constantly access to information of its users.
L "site team that handles data studied the statistics on the situation in love and the day of the Saint Valentine, the turnout in the mid-term elections of 2010 and a national index of happiness (with the information available - only the champions of freedom digital have long argued that the site could make available its treasure trove of data to others for research purposes).
But users of Facebook know that the site notes that they like it or not - in exchange for power play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of kilometres, the site is authorized to access your information.
But what happens when users of Facebook are part of a survey that they have not even heard of?
While researchers have clearly defined instructions on how to collect the information other than through the Internet, it is anything else online.
"I do not believe that a large number of users have already thought about the fact that a researcher can study their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the Laboratory of Knowledge of London, according to a 2006 study he led by observing the Facebook walls of its students.
"They know, exchanges were seen by their friends."
And then there is the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study to be completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on the wall of an user.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two entirely different things," says Neil Selwyn.
That is why, despite his experience as a researcher, Neil Selwyn think a pad and pen remain the best tools that can be used.
"Nothing can replace the real world and the contact with the people," he says.
"The social studies are expected to address the social aspect - and the social, it is not at a computer."
