7 lessons of the interview lost to Steve Jobs, film this week
After the death of Steve Jobs on 5 October, some have compared to Henry Ford - distinguished by the technical innovations and inventor of the modern computer.
But what the fans of Apple may find more revealing in an interview of Steve Jobs found recently and which will be released this week in the first part of a film on the major markets, is how this creative spirit had understood the process and work flow of products.
It was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. Identified with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a breeding of organizational charts - a man who believed that many business leaders had a "disease their that suggests that a great idea is 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work between a great idea of a product of exception."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds." This series traces the birth of the computer, and he sits down for more than a hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
By then, it was about 10 years ago that Steve Jobs had to leave Apple. It was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at a popular adoption of the Internet.
When a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he stated that the main copies have disappeared in transport.
It is only after the death of Steve Jobs that a full video is found in the garage the director.
This video, slightly, is the basis of the 68 -minute film entitled Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will air in cinemas on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate the in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic to expose philosophies technological and business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs is clearly his thoughts, in an effort to provide a clear answer.
There are also times when perfectionism of Steve Jobs resurfaced, where he seems anxious to hear the issues of Cringely, kicking it elbow to accelerate to questions or issues of greatest importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prescient on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs assesses what it sees as good or bad in other businesses and her own vision on the future of the computer.
It is one thing to read the posthumous assessments of the career of Steve Jobs, but there is something gross and based on the man we see here, the dreamer anxiety on the eve of the magnitude.
He has a vision of how things can be and should be.
It explains and then put in place.
Here's a quick summary of seven sequences of Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
"During all these years, I have always asked:" Why are you doing things? "And the answers are always the same:" oh, simply because they have to be. ""
No one knows why, no one is thinking in depth to things in a company.
That is what I discovered.
Steve Jobs is giving details of its efforts to simplify the accounting at Apple.
Puzzled as to how the costs were registered - it often begins with a "standard cost" of a rule of thumb, and then adjusted with a "variation" - it has developed an automated plant that guaranteed the precise calculation of trade costs.
On the opportunity to play a round to Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the story of the "Blue Box" that he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack into telephone networks and call for free long-distance.
The device has been the subject of much written in advance, but the euphoria of Steve Jobs here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak have tested the box using a public phone, then an appeal by linking a network AT to another while avoiding as many satellites as possible.
"We enveloppions the ball of different things half a dozen times and you hurliez in the public telephone and it was a minute later on the telephone public next door," Jobs said with a laugh.
"We were young and through the Blue Box, we learned that we could ourselves create something capable of controlling billions of dollars of infrastructure in the world."
We do not know much every two, but we have been able to invent a small thing capable of great things. It was a lesson incredible, and I do not believe that Apple would have ever existed without it.
Steve Jobs is telling a wonderful turn that he and Wozniak have developed: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night by posing as Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are convened in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices in laughter just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love with technology (and lobbying of Bill Hewlett):
In the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to make a counter, it is the number of Bill Hewlett in the phone book and gives him a call.
Shortly after their 20 -minute conversation, Steve Jobs is a summer job part-time in Hewlett-Packard.
"This had an impact on me." C "was the only company that I had seen in this article and this has formed my definition of a business and how employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of the HP employees to visit the research laboratories at the company, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the "first desktop computer ever designed."
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small tube. I fell in love.
The adolescent that j "was returned in HP and began to write programs for this machine.
On the improvisation of innovation:
Several times in the interview, Steve Jobs speaks to invent new products on a whim.
Early in his career, when he moved to sell a few printed circuit boards, a customer asked to assemble a computer.
Working with only 30 days of credit, it had to take care of the assembly and delivery of devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember large disputes... I was yelling, claiming that I would have five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I am out and went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make $15 and which was incredibly reliable.
Large enterprises that run out of steam:
Well before it is revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated the way many industrial leaders would be wrong and losing control of their market share.
"Recognise that you work with IBM and Xerox, you are a better or a better printer, and after?"
You have the monopoly of the market, therefore the company does not meet more successful.
Sales and marketing can evolve, so [it is these types of people] that eventually lead businesses and product are available to the "gap decision-making.
The engineering product which led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who cannot imagine designing a good product versus a bad product - the manual work required.
This is what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could hold all the computer industry.
She could have ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90 s...
They uprooted the defeat to victory.
On innovation as an art form:
"A huge part of manual work between a great idea of an extraordinary income... As you develop this idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a great deal on its subtleties.
There are trade-offs... Some things that you can't do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories as well.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind these (concepts) by assembling to each other.
Finally, decisions are taken by personal taste. This is to try to expose you to the best products that men have created, and try to make these things to the product that you create.
Picasso once said that the good artists copy and that the great artists steal.
We have always ashamed to fly excellent ideas.
It is part of what makes Macintosh. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply proved to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If this is for the computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another area.
