The law firm of Clément, PLLC Bancroft, was among the two dozen firms that have helped to sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society Fédéraliste (Society), a group of dedicated to defend the legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, is one of the trade associations who challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business (National Federation of Independent Business).
Another sponsor was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc, which presents a huge financial stake in the outcome of the dispute.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel a few hours after the conference of the court on the case.
Was there, among other things, Mitch McConnell, top Republican of the Senate and sworn opponent of the bill of health.
The featured dinner guests? Scalia and Thomas.
This is not new: the two judges have been present at the events of the Fédéraliste for years.
And there is nothing that goes against the rules of conduct.
In fact, the judges are exempt from code of conduct that governs the actions of federal judges.
If they were, they would probably by the Code of Canon 4 C, which states: "A judge may attend fundraising organizations related to the right and although the judge may not be a stakeholder, a guest of honour, or appearing on the program of such an event."
Nevertheless, the mere presence of Scalia and Thomas close to two law firms of the case, as well as a business with a financial interest, was enough to alarm the activists of government ethics.
"This violation of ethics and superb indifference to the code contradicts the statements of several judges that the Court will meet the same rules for all other federal judges," said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"The judges drinking and dining and a fundraising gala with lawyers who have cases pending before the court."
Their presence and their participation in the collection of funds of this event removes any claim of impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little regard for the criticism that they mix too easily the affairs of the court with the agenda of groups such as the Fédéraliste.
And the wife of Thomas, Ginni, is a conservative activist, specifically.
Furthermore, the Conservatives argue that it is the judge Elena Kagan who has a problem of ethics, and not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan was solicitor general of the Obama administration when the first opposition to the law have been laid in the court of first instance.
His critics have pushed for Kagan to recuse herself to hear the case, saying that she was too invested in defence of the law to be impartial.
Kagan has given no indication that it would do so.
