Severe warnings from the Pentagon on the potential reduction of defence
The Secretary of Defense, Leon Panetta, has increased the pressure on the Congress on Monday, warning that the imminent automatic budget cuts would undermine national security. It triggered a chain reaction of financial corridors of the Pentagon to the battlefields of Afghanistan, as well as the raising of civilians.
The Pentagon was already $450 billion in reductions for the next decade, but is concerned now that an additional amount of $600 or more cuts are imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
"The impacts of these cuts would be devastating for the department," Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said that the failure of Congress to reach a budget agreement resulting in what is known as sequestration, would result in 23% of reductions and the freezing of many new projects.
"A significant reduction, and applied indiscriminately, would make most of our vessels and construction projects unenforceable - you cannot buy three quarters of a ship or a building - and seriously damage to other modernization efforts," Panetta wrote to senators.
"We would also be forced to separate us from a number of our civilian staff and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we should almost certainly send civilians on leave without pay in order to achieve the objective."
"These changes would undermine the faith of those who support our military and seriously damage our preparation."
The reductions would ultimately affect the fighting troops, Panetta continues.
"While the funding of the accounts of contingency operations abroad is not directly affected by the sequestration, the war efforts would be negatively affected by the disruptions in the core budgets," warned Panetta.
"The Contracting staff would be reduced, resulting in delays in contracts and the supervision of the contract that support the war."
"The staff manager salaries would be reduced, leading to delays in payments to suppliers of war, and the legal and policy support would be disrupted."
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days earlier, requesting details on the potential impact of the automatic cuts on the Ministry of Defence.
"The consequence of a sequestration on the Department of Defence would trigger a rapid decline of the United States as the undisputed world of military power."
"We are strongly opposed to this drastic action," said the senators in a joint statement Monday afternoon at the time of the publication of the letter to Panetta.
"This is not a consequence with which we can live, and this is certainly not the one that we should impose."
"The sequestration is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it should not have to happen."
That the letter to Panetta and the recent warnings of senators are increasing the pressure for a budget compromise or appeal to exempt the Pentagon cuts, remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly virulent about possible cuts, even if he managed to the highest position of the Pentagon with years of expertise of the budget to Congress and the White House and knowing that it was faced with difficult choices.
In a press conference last week, the defense secretary painted a bleak picture of what could occur - a military with a shell but no core.
"This is a ship without sailors."
"It is a brigade without bullets."
"It is a fighter pilot, without enough trained."
"This is a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs who do not have enough trained soldiers able to accomplish the mission," Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It is a strength depressed, poorly prepared and unable to cope with potential adversaries."
"De facto, it invites aggression."
In an addendum to its letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta has set out specifically how new reductions could "generate significant operational risks response time to crises, conflicts and disasters; severe limits to our ability to deploy and engage in the world; and risk assumed unacceptable in combat operations future."
And Panetta said that some of the major defence projects could one for the axe, including those already tested and some fair in the early stages of planning.
This list included the F35 Joint Strike Fighter, a new bomber planned ballistic submarine, the new generation, the new warship coastline and the new vehicle, which would replace the Humvee of the army and the navy.
Ending the development and testing of the F35 could generate $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but his supporters say that this is an essential step to improve and response to potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to identify a lie
A look at recent headlines indicates how the deception and lies are omnipresent in daily life.
The Republican nominee Herman Cain is to exchange of allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
The directors of Penn State have been accused of perjury for allegedly covered reports that a football coach to retire was sexually abusing boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was taken by an open microphone saying to U.S. President Barack Obama that the Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie destroyed careers and convulsé countries.
The member of Congress from New York and celebrity of the Internet Anthony Weiner, is past for a fool by issuing denials quickly contradicted by evidence irrefutable.
The former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of violations of campaign finance related to coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, none of anyone who has lived the history will never forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton has triggered by lying in his second term on ever his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating on tests of the school and the university are legion.
There have been cases where teachers have the responses by the tests students to see on their assessments of performance.
The mentors who teach the opposite should send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many let's meet deception?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are lies.
Another study showed that the foreign lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detect or identify lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game similar to, say, charades, where the objective is to scream: I had, "the detection of deception is a branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities with conducted a thorough search of such projects, including in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths on lies were all.
The liars look at you in the eye.
They bégayent turn red, or if not always.
Not to conclude that the liars are difficult to detect and difficult to uncover.
A lie detector qualified can discover the truth by examining the structure of the declaration, the micro-expressions facial, training of the issue and the response time.
I spent several years to review of the scientific results in the vast body and always emerge of knowledge about the deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern jurisdiction that is easy to learn and useful to navigate in our complex world - especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or management.
The good liars are skilled to read the other, at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that the extroverts lie more than introverts, men say more lies "citizen-centred" while women say more lies "focused on other" - usually to protect the feelings of someone - that married people less often lie to their partners that unmarried (but that the lies that they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are seen as a miscreant, the other will feel less guilty when you lie.
How can you say whether a person?
First of all, observe the normal behaviour of your subject.
This is called "establish benchmarks."
This helps to provide a reference point for measuring subsequent changes.
Watch the posture of your subject, the laughter, quality voice.
You need to know if someone is normally its feet in order not to launch charges unfair when you see the feet in the middle of the meeting.
And then look for signs of behaviour misleading verbal and non-verbal cues.
Consider these indices as of red flags, not evidence of deception.
People can misleading around the upper body when trying to remember their history, they can point their feet to the door, look towards an exit, change of posture significantly or present a relief of "post-interview" - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult issues are.
The interrogators often falsely indicate that the maintenance is completed just to seek to trigger the reaction post-interview.
Also, be careful in the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson has gone wrong in the past while claiming that murdered his wife was alive, triggering a national search for the envelope.
Individuals can also use a misleading language outpaced: "I did not have sexual relations with that woman Miss Lewinsky..." or repeat fully a difficult issue.
The indicators are the most common are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "language" at its response to a question difficult: "Well... To tell the truth... If I remember goods... To my knowledge."
This makes the perceptual response rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for the detection of lies, but the development of skills to recognize the deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid the victimization by con artists in their professional and personal lives.
