A few days after the Obama administration has threatened to delay the approval of a pipeline project between Canada and the Gulf of Mexico - are causing the anger of unions while appeasing environmentalists - the company seeking to build the pipeline said that it is ready to redirect the project to the back on track.
Transcanada said Monday evening that it will move the pipeline from the ecologically sensitive dunes of Nebraska, and is confident that the project will still win approval.
The company announced the decision at a press conference on Capitol Hill Nebraska.
The Journal of TransCanada, Alex Pourbax, says that the company remains confident that it will eventually obtain the approval of a pipeline, but with a different route.
This follows the announcement by the State Department last week that it would delay its decision to grant a federal permit for the project until he received new studies of potential routes to avoid areas of Nebraska and the Ogallala aquifer, extensive sources of groundwater.
"This is a very real way forward," said Lee Terry, a Republican from Nebraska to Fox News.
The new environment review commissioned by the Department of State would probably have postponed any decision until 2013, after the elections next year, although officials deny the involvement of the policy in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as "the decision of the Department of State, and expressed its support.
The 2.735 km oil pipeline would extend from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would carry 700.000 barrels a day from the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
To do this, it would cross six states.
It is hated by environmentalists, but loved by working groups, which have capitalized on the estimated 20 000 jobs related to the pipeline.
But the Nebraska legislators opposed to the plan that are pushing legislation to force the remoteness of the area of Sand Hills and the Ogallala aquifer, a major source of drinking water and irrigation.
The Environmental Impact Statement of the State Department found that the project would only limited adverse environmental impacts, but the energy industry stated that the Inspector General of the Department ordered a separate investigation of the review process, focusing on two issues.
One is that a lobbyist hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliott, who was a campaign adviser to Hillary Clinton in 2008, would be a conflict of interest for the program.
The other is whether a company that was hired to conduct the initial study was inappropriate in its relationship with TransCanada.
