Adversity climate has slowed the economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, Sinaloa unemployment and informality have increased, foreign investment has fallen and the economy contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, this is the first year of Government of Mario López Valdez, auto-appelé of change, which has generated great expectations as regards the advances of the economy, but given the adversity climate at the beginning of the year, the increase was not observed in exchange, there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
Low temperatures in February, share of loss of trillions for the agricultural sector, have limited opportunities for the state's economy for growth, have caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic decline of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which has affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the report of assignments by the frozen by the Mexican Council of Rural Development Series, there was $582 million in damages 835 hectares, including a 78.03 percent suffered damage total and the rest of 21.07 percent have suffered partial damage, the major crops have been affected vegetables, corn, and chickpea.
The decline in economic activity generated, until November, a steady rise in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the unemployment rate in the State in the first three quarters of the year has accelerated, because for the January to March 55 mile 053 sinaloens were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Active Population Economics, in the second quarter the rate is now 5.28 percent and the July to September the average continued to increase up to 6.19 percent, a rate that represents more than 74 thousand sinaloens unemployed, up from the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in the Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to the economist López Gerardo Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Social and Economic Sciences of the UAS, rising unemployment can be explained in terms of indirect actions carried out by public policy.
"That is an increase in unemployment which is due to various factors, among which the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people with the dollars some way that this is not easy to work for the win, they invest and use it in something," he says.
Migration held
López Cervantes reported that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad, the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because when they have already struggling to find work, these people to stay here and seek sources of work, which means that unemployment increase," déclaré-t-il.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the labour market sinaloen worsens in considering the high level of lack of seriousness that predominates between working conditions, according to INEGI, the 60.38 percent of the population involved in this state is working without pay as worker in any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and the lack of seriousness, another reason to lag for the state are low wages, the entity has the lowest in the Country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute for Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecast.
The average monthly revenues of workers sinaloens was, until September, 5 mile 352 pesos, well below the national average, which stands at 7 mile 375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Apart from the decline in economic activity and rising unemployment, in 2011 had the greatest reduction Foreign Direct Investment of the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the FDI of the state was $630 thousand $697, a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to 5 million 143 thousand $312 recorded in the same period the previous year.
In turn, the Secretariat of Economic Development of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17.280 trillion pesos per year, mainly by the companies of the service sector.
Debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the Government of the State sought in July at the public approval of a credit of 3 trillion pesos, to investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipes, with the objective to reactivate the economy, the approval of the Congress of the State was 2.600 trillion pesos and up to the November there were no benefit of debt in any sector of the economy of the state.
Reactions
For the representatives of the business sector, the first year of Government of Mario López Valdés demonstrates a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Loredo Miguel López, President of the National Chamber of Industry Transformation, said that in 2011 there has been no harmonisation of the wishes of the different sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of the economy of Sinaloa during this year was really very poor, we must work hard to recover lost ground this year, in 2012 we must double our effort, it was necessary to align the effort of all and particularly the already synchronized of this new team of Government, hope that next year will be much better," he says.
Slow economic
loredo López said that events such as the beginning of the year were the economy of the state and have restricted its performance and growth.
"The bottom fluxe economic product of several events, among which the frozen, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that is fast enough to generate economic dynamism that provides an acceptable level he flow in the trial, products and services, and therefore, at the end of the year we close much below expectations that we had," he says.
Redefine the mission
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, President of the National Confederation of the Republic of Sinaloa Mexican stated that it wants to harness the State to productive activities more dynamism.
"In general terms we observed that it worked, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefined the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that the blast the full potential of material and human resources of Sinaloa," he says.
Much to do
The President of the Coparmex stressed the importance of a vision of a better future that channels the efforts of the Government.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development a few advances, but it is important to develop a long term to long term," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in the way of public policy management.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that it has worked and the Government is aware of the fact that there is still much to do," he says.
