Japan Returns after the earthquake
The GDP increase a 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption to end the spiral of decline from the beginning of March
Since March the Japanese economy was crippled, or even after the devastating earthquake that has become nuclear crisis, the worst disaster the country Japanese since the Second World War.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo have calculated the material losses to $300.000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to be mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of falling, the data of the Gross Domestic Product between July and September were used to turn the page: GDP increased 1.5% from the previous quarter and a 6% annualized rate.
That the second quarter - for the Japanese, the tax year begins in March 2012 - requires, in addition, the highest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is due, in part, by the resumption of equipment additions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, businesses have increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of non-interrompue increase.
However, the real challenge of the Japanese economy is based exclusively on the Keynesian stimulus that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, use the shortcomings to grow from zero.
Japan has awakened mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently represents 60% of GDP.
This variable has increased 1%, driven by the increase in spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment.
The stigma of yen
Tokyo has recovered to the internal market when the Japanese yen - the currency - has become a "refuge" values elected by investors fleeing the debt crisis in eurozone and forecasts from the United States, a privilege that weighs as a slab in the accounts of export companies.
With a divided stronger, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country with a line of floating economic is determined by the health of large groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, have been responsible for their poor results between July and September the assessment of the yen.
While the markets continue their seats in the outlying countries of EU, the Government of Yoshihiko Noda be bullish.
"We have to follow the risks remain, as the deterioration of certain foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said yesterday the Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa.
And, indeed, the prospects are not at all encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) noted that the majority of countries provided in September clearer signals of economic slowdown.
The indicator that anticipates the inflection points of the global economy has highlighted that the major powers are constrained.
Because it dropped four decimal places up to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
He has even been above the average, which is in the level 100, dropping eight decimal places up to 99.13 points.
Athens is again the doubts
Papadimos said that adjustments will be approved, but the Conservatives will sign a written commitment
With the risk premium peripheral triggered and uncertainty relocated in parks, Greece continues to become entangled in the maze that led to the exit of the great European debt crisis.
The sensation that the "consensus" of the new Greek Government of transition is imposed by the requirements of Brussels by a real conviction of political forces is beginning to be confirmed by the facts.
While the new Prime Minister, Lukas Papadimos reported yesterday that there is no other alternative for the structural reforms and that the period of one hundred days has established in the designation may be short for application, the leader of the Conservative party New Democracy, Antonis Samaras, provided that he would not support the new austerity measures in no case and reiterated its demand new elections for the scheduled date of 19 February.
"The main task of this Government is to apply the decisions of the summit of 26 October," said Papadimos when he opened yesterday a parliamentary debate that will end tomorrow with a vote of confidence for the new Executive.
A package of 24 programs to boost employment, the reform of the disciplinary code of civil servants and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, the message of Samaras No. of doubts about its position: "We are committed to helping the Government of transition, but we are committed to nothing more."
The conservative leader went a step further in his pulse that EU and IMF, organizations that must release the 8.000 million that Athens requires with urgency, and has made it clear that he will not approve any letter of commitment of the adjustments.
But the European Commission, irritated by the impact caused by the lengths of the referendum in Papandreu, reiterated yesterday that his requirement is firm: it will provide assistance if the new Government and the leaders of the main parties "third do not sign a written commitment without ambiguities as soon as possible."
The voice of Economic Affairs, Amadeu Altafaj, explained that the inspectors of the troika would return "very quickly" to Athens to discuss with the new Government "the elements necessary to pay for the sixth tranche" of 8.000 million, even if there is a final date.
The Greek still have much to do.
The Queen Sofía: "This are instruments for progress and hope"
The Queen said the "dominant" of Spain with regard to this type of finance
Spain "was taking place at the global level in the role of Micro-finances."
The Queen Sofía recalled that the country has become in the last two decades the second donor in the world with regard to this instrument of cooperation that the "essence" lies in the fact that it is a "instrument for social progress, justice and hope for a better future for all humanity, based on confidence in the human being."
The Queen opened the V-e yesterday of the Microcredit Summit in Valladolid with the certainty that "there is no doubt" that this type of operations are "absolutely necessary" to achieve the Millennium Development Goals established by the United Nations for 2015, and, "very specifically, for the purpose of the reduction to half the volume of people with incomes below a dollar a day, which is the" poverty line ."
Spain "continues to work" to enlarge the network of beneficiaries "in all corners of the planet, and undertake this task with" responsibility, "said the Queen Sofía, who hoped that the initiatives and inputs origins during the Summit, which will last until Thursday," guarantee the creation of new capabilities and better opportunities for the poor, and especially for women, "the main beneficiaries of these loans.
"We have achieved many objectives" and "we we face many challenges."
The Microcredit Summit is intended not only as a forum for debate, but also as the platform from which we must give "two goals."
And, Her Majesty explained that the objective is that at the end of 2015 there were 175 million poor families who have been assigned to these financial services and that one hundred million of these families out of poverty in which they live now.
The momentum in the design of micro-credits in Spain and in the rest of the world "has followed the trail initiated a few years ago in a manner" by pioneer Muhammad Yunus, "said the Queen Sofía as an" act of justice and due recognition. "
And she described the father of this instrument as a "idealistic admirable in the universal cause of the fight against poverty," the work which it is since 15 years ago, when the Queen travelled to Bangladesh to check on the ground its lending policy.
This experience was followed a year later by the first World Summit in Washington and other meetings such as those in Côte d'Ivoire in 1999, Canada in 2006, and "in every meeting I have seen a continuing evolution," explained Her Majesty, whose relationship with this project brought him yesterday the term "family head" meeting in Valladolid on the part of the "banking on the poor."
Finally, the Queen Sofía has finished his speech by encouraging the audience to participate in the debate and in the search for solutions to make progress in the fight against poverty.
"Imperative etic"
The Minister of Foreign Affairs, Trinidad Jiménez, warned that solidarity "is an ethical imperative" for any democratic state.
In this sense, it stated that it would be a mistake to vinculer cooperation with developing countries in times of economic prosperity, because it is a "continuing obligation."
Jiménez took the view that the microcredit involves "a serious political and rigorous dedicated to the eradication of poverty," and now "more than ever" governments of developed countries must work under the criteria of solidarity and do not allow it to be the victim of the cutbacks.
For Spain, microcredit is "one of the main lines of cooperation for development."
The Secretary of State for International Cooperation, Soraya Rodriguez, applauded the "success" of giving "confidence" to persons "which excluded all close the door"; and the Mayor of Valladolid, Francisco Javier León de la Riva, welcomed the people in a city that "opens its doors contaminated the spirit of solidarity."
The CDU proposes to elect the European president by universal suffrage
The first day of the congress of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), Monday 14 November, Leipzig, was held without any real difficulty for Chancellor Angela Merkel, but also president of the Christian Democratic Party.
The future of Europe was not originally planned in the program but has emerged in the fall, including to meet activists who feel the policy of the Government too lax towards the Greeks today and perhaps of Italians tomorrow.
The motion on the presidency of the European Commission, proposed by management, was adopted almost unanimously.
About 1001 delegates, only nine were against and ten abstained.
The standing ovation of several minutes, that was given, at the end of their interventions, Angela Merkel, and then, a few hours later, Wolfgang Schäuble, the very Europhile Finance Minister, provided no room for doubt.
The main strategy of Chancellor - and of the motion - is a slogan: the response to the crisis "is not less Europe but more Europe."
Not only because Europe is peace but because "nine million jobs depend directly on the euro."
For the Chancellor, "the time has come to a breakthrough in Europe."
This could result in changes to the Lisbon Treaty to strengthen the control of the European Union on the budgetary policies of the countries in the euro area, but it could also lead to the election of the President of the European Commission by universal suffrage "to give a face to Europe."
At least this is one of the proposals in the motion adopted by Congress whose inspiration is clearly Wolfgang Schäuble.
Of course, it is unlikely that the twenty-seven agree quickly on this revolution: Britain is hostile and the leaders of the CDU believe that Nicolas Sarkozy is also important.
But the milestone is made.
Similarly, the delegates rejected by an overwhelming majority the proposal to balance the weight of each country to the Executive Board of the European Central Bank based on the weight of each economy, which of course was to strengthen the weight of Germany.
To appease the climate within his party, the Chancellor has multiplied the references to Konrad Adenauer and Helmut Kohl but it has not sought to win its conference on the backs of "small" European countries or countries in difficulty quick to criticise the arrogant Germany.
If the motion on Europe devotes a section to the importance of the "Franco-German friendship," Angela Merkel did not mention France.
Except in hollow.
Recalling that two centuries ago, Leipzig had been at the heart of a bloody battle.
In fact, this was one of the most humiliating defeats of Napoleon's army.
