After the allowances, the UMP and the government launched the offensive on the judgments.
Nicolas Sarkozy will be Tuesday, November 15, in Bordeaux to visit a child allowance fund, and give a speech on the theme - recurrent since 2007 - of the fight against fraud and the social handouts.
And to accompany this offensive, which share a willingness to make savings in a context of rigour, but is no less heralds an axis of the presidential campaign on the right, the majority wants to focus on the judgments.
First in an aim of budgetary savings: the government plans to impose to employees of the private a fourth day of waiting before taking charge of a work stoppage.
Clearly, without specific company agreement, an employee who falls ill would lose four days of salary, therefore at least 15% of their monthly income.
A measure of anger, but that would be EUR 280 million, according to Les Echos.
And that would be accompanied by another measure, more symbolic: officials to impose a day of waiting not compensated in the event of a work stoppage (they have not waiting period, for three days in the private).
While these issues are under discussion, the majority is also the issue of fraud, targeting this time for work stoppages.
"The controls will be much more important and, in addition, if you are caught, you will pay," warned Xavier Bertrand at the micro RTL, Sunday 13 November.
As in other cases, the effects of announcement seem somewhat disproportionate with the reality of the fraud to work stoppages.
It is indeed the subject since 2002 of a constant monitoring and offensive policies that have most often borne fruit.
The French not sicker than elsewhere in Europe.
We focus first on the national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (NHIF), more than EUR 237 million of daily allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute of Research and Documentation in health economics, the daily allowances accounted for 2008 5% of health spending, with EUR 11.3 billion.
Of this amount, 46% were the maternity leave and work accidents, and 54% were the judgments, or EUR 6.2 billion.
And 2.5% of health spending.
In 2010, the French have been an average of 14.5 days of absence from work, compared with 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the group Alma Consulting.
An average that masks differences some: another survey, published in 2007 by the career management site Monster.com, showed that 75 percent of the 40 000 French employees surveyed reported that they had taken any day of judgment.
Another study, this time from the Health Insurance, states that in 2010, 37% of the judgments were of less than 8 days, 22% of 8 to 14 days, 15% of 15 days to a month, 15% of one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, the French are not more likely than elsewhere to work stoppages.
A 2010 study by two researchers from CNRS showed that between 1994 and 2001, the rate of overall absence (for health reasons or not), France, between 10% and 11%, compared to 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the UK or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Fraud to disease is very little in the black economy.
As to the fraud, it is only a small scale.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 that the controls are systematic on the judgments of more than 45 days.
In 2008, on 1.5 million controls, the CNAM found that 13% of the 285 000 made for judgments of short duration were "unjustified or too long," 37 050.
In the case of judgments of more than 45 days, systematically controlled, there were 11% of cases "inadequate or unjustified" on 1.2 million, or 132 000.
In total, 169 000 cases "unjustified," on several million employees who had an interruption.
A figure that represents very little about, for example, to that of the black economy.
