Papadémos: Greece will need to implement a new adjustment plan
Greece will need a new adjustment program to restore its economy.
That is what said Monday, November 14, the Prime Minister, Lucas Papadémos, before Parliament, adding that the hundred days given to its unity government would not be sufficient to accomplish this task.
"To continue the efforts of recovery of the economy, we need the support of our European partners and a new budgetary adjustment programme," said the head of government, who made his first public speech at the opening of the debate on the confidence vote in Parliament on Wednesday.
The implementation of the decisions taken at the top of the euro area on 27 October will be the "primary task" of the new government, because the country's participation in the euro area "is at stake," he added.
As a result, Mr. Papadémos has projected that the deficit of the country will be reduced to around 9% "of GDP by the end of the year, up from 10.6% in 2010 and 15.7% in 2009.
