We must legalise euthanasia and assisted suicide, said a committee of experts
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada
In palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians work together to ensure better palliative care, and that, beyond the cases of cancer.
Canadian society lives in the denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to speak with their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make provisions to this effect.
This is one of the conclusions of a report of the Royal Society of Canada, with six experts in various areas, including ethics, law and medicine.
The Committee recommends the government to amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when this is done with a patient is found to be competent to take such a decision.
From the outset, the experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, who compared the quality of the death in 40 countries of the world.
If Canada is ranked 10 th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to talk about death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, we are the experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the wish that most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them eventually die in hospital.
Overall, the country, it is in Quebec that this rate is the highest, with 86% of deaths at the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report comes to conclusions that are contrary to the position of the federal government, which has already said it does not want to change anything in the Criminal Code on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all the countries where these approaches are legalised or decriminalised, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuses in the application, i.e., the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on persons not competent or not consented.
On the contrary, said yesterday in teleconference Jocelyn Downie, a co-signatory of the report, we would have many more cases of these excesses specifically in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not permitted.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"The assisted suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians support euthanasia
It should be recalled that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe that it would allow persons at the end of life to alleviate their suffering, Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalising euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of elderly or disabled persons has less value.
For those who assisted suicide, the surveyed feel 41% that they should not be pursued.
In terms of maintaining or cessation of care for a patient, the situation is less clear, say the authors of the report.
Also, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it be included in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a refusal legally valid is not a criminal.
The Committee of Experts also requires that health professionals are trained to the duty to respect a refusal of end-of-life care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
In palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians work together to ensure better palliative care, and that, beyond the cases of cancer.
Finally, in terms of palliative sedation or terminal, already widely used in the institutions of Canadian health, the Committee requests that it be considered, when it is not used to reduce physical pain, such as euthanasia, and is subject to the same procedures.
Reserves other experts
Some experts in the field of health law have already reservations concerning the conclusions of the report of the Royal Society of Canada.
I am Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, described as "extreme" position experts signatories of the report, among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia for the terminally ill.
"This opens the door to a situation where everyone who is tired of life and would have more than 18 years ago could ask to have it assistance to commit suicide," said Mr. Deschamps, who had consulted yesterday a summary of the report.
I Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to place the autonomy of the person above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
However, "in society," he says, it is bound and constraints. "
The specialist health law Margaret Somerville has also expressed "strong opposition" to the conclusions of the report, which it referred to as "manifesto pro-euthanasia."
Margaret Somerville, which is a member of the Royal Society of Canada, in particular the data in the report about the lack of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide were legalised, the Netherlands and Oregon.
