A Russian scientist helped Iran's nuclear program
A Russian scientific, Vycheslav Danilenko, helped Iran develop a detonator with a nuclear weapon, "said Monday, an American NGO specializing in the nuclear risk.
The Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) is based on the recent report by the International Agency for Atomic (IAEA) and other documents filed by the U.N. agency to identify the researcher.
The IAEA reported last week of its "serious concerns" about "possible military dimension" of Iran's nuclear programme.
According to ISIS out in IAEA documents, Mr. Danilenko, born in 1934, had worked for three decades from the 60 s in a nuclear Soviet military in Chelyabinsk (Urals), and would have been involved in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds by explosion.
In 1989 or 1991, it would have left the centre to establish a company producing "nano-diamants" in Kiev.
The economic difficulties of its society led to contact the Iranian Embassy in Ukraine in 1995.
It would then have cooperated in the Iranian program from 1996 to 2002, before his return in Russia.
In its last report, the IAEA is "of strong indications that the development by Iran of a nuclear detonation system" has been helped by the work of a foreign expert, who not only knew this technique, but which, as a Member State has informed the Agency, worked for most of his career on this technology within the military nuclear programme of his country of origin. "
The crimes and offences anti-Muslim increased by 50%
The crimes and offences against Muslims have increased by almost 50% from 2009 to 2010, while at the same time, other racial and religious violence have slightly decreased or little progress, according to statistics from the FBI made public Monday.
According to these figures, the total number of violence perpetrated against Muslims increased from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, or 49% increase, compared with 13% of violence against Catholics, a decrease of 4% of offences against Jews and an overall increase of 14% of crimes and offences anti-religious.
The total number of "hate crimes" has increased marginally to 6 628 cases, including 47.3% driven by differences of race and 20% by differences of religion, according to the FBI.
"After a decline in 2009, it is disturbing to see these crimes and offences increase again," said the human rights organisation Human rights First, "the increase in anti-Muslim violence is particularly significant," the organization said in a news release.
"Human Rights First has long stressed that violence against Muslims, and all forms of hate crimes, should be considered a serious violation of human rights," said one of the managers of the organization, Paul Legendre.
"The U.S. government can and must do more to address these abuses," he says, believing that this could be accomplished by improving police reports on "hate crimes."
The "hate crime" in the U.S. federal law is a legacy of the era of the struggle for civil rights.
This legislation had been adopted after the death of Martin Luther King to punish violence related to race, skin colour, religion, origin and now.
