Austria
Recording of a "golden rule" budget in the constitution
The government of Christian Democrat / Social Democrat coalition in power in Austria decided Tuesday to enter in the constitution a "golden rule" budget to reduce public deficits and avoid a possible degradation by the rating agencies sovereign rating of Austria (triple A).
It is the Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann who has even announced this decision at the end of a Council of Ministers, while Austrian public debt is 74.6%, well above the 60% criterion maximum set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If the solvency of Austria was lowered only one notch, from AAA to AA +, we should pay three billion euros of interest in addition each year," argued the Christian Democrat Vice-Chancellor and Minister of Foreign Affairs, Michael Spindelegger.
Austria is responding to a request from the summit in Brussels of the member countries of the euro area of 26 October: the Heads of State and Government had claimed the listing by the end of 2012 the reduction of public deficits and a return to the balance of public accounts in the constitution or a law of equal value.
The system introduced by the Austrian Government is close to the "German model," Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule."
By 2017, the structural public deficit should decrease each year of 0.75% of the gross domestic product (GDP) and, beginning in 2017, the structural public deficit of the federal state will not exceed 0.35% of GDP, while the regional states as well as the Commons will be required to submit balanced budgets.
The objective is to increase by 2020/21 public debt under the criterion of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty.
Strong yen
Noda threat of a new intervention in the foreign exchange market
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda, warned on Tuesday that the Japanese authorities would once again in the foreign exchange market if the yen should continue to rise.
"We will do as we did the last time if we see excessive volatility" in the exchange rate of the yen, "said Mr. Noda in the Senate.
On Tuesday, the yen was not far from the historical levels that prompted the Japanese authorities to intervene on 31 October.
That day, Tokyo sold heavily yen against dollars to lower the value of the Japanese currency which had just set a new record of 1945 relative to the dollar.
But the yen is regularly picked up since, boosted by purchases of investors who see it as a "safe haven" in these uncertain times of global economic slowdown and debt crisis in Europe.
The dollar rose Tuesday below 77 yen and the euro briefly fell below the symbolic 105 yen, close to levels that triggered the last intervention.
Before the financial crisis of 2008-2009, the dollar was quoted at around 120 yen and the euro more than 160 yen.
The outbreak of the currency Japanese exports of the archipelago as it builds the cost of products Made in Japan and reduces the value of income from abroad by Japanese firms, when they convert in national currency.
"Japan struggle to rebuild" since the earthquake and tsunami on March 11 that devastated the region of Tohoku (northeastern), pointed out that Mr. Noda is concerned that the rise of the yen kills the egg in the fragile recovery.
The world's third largest economy returned to growth in the third quarter - 1.5% compared to the quarter précédent- for the first time in a year, thanks to a rebound in exports and household consumption sealed by the disaster.
But the Prime Minister found that the high cost of the yen did not reflect "the economic foundation of Japan."
The Minister of Finance, Jun Azumi, called the Bank of Japan (BOJ), which opened Tuesday a two-day meeting of its Board of monetary policy, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen.
But the deputy governor of the institution, Hirohide Yamaguchi, warned that the BOJ had already taken the "appropriate measures," suggesting that no additional monetary easing was to wait until Wednesday.
At its last meeting in late October, the central bank has increased by 5.000 billion yen (47 billion euros) its purchases of Treasury bills, to 55.000 billion yen (519 billion euros) the ceiling of the amounts it spends on purchases of securities financial various for flooding the market with liquidity.
