Energy policy:
The facts must outweigh the dogmas
If there is one subject that cannot treat based on considerations of short term or under the "emotion, it is the energy policy.
The availability and cost of the electricity directly affect purchasing power and on the competitiveness of enterprises.
It is healthy that an election date is an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the role of nuclear power.
The debate will be successful only if it explores all of the economic, social and environmental consequences of proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, the demographic change will result in a doubling of the application of electricity by 2050, at least to deprive a huge part of the world's population of a vital element.
At the same time, we must address the scarcity of fossil resources to continue to produce the electricity, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases to combat climate change, a subject disappeared from the debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to abandon the use of nuclear power.
This is not the case of Belgium, who submits his motorcycle to the need to find a source of replacement able to substitute for, nor of Switzerland, who intends to just stop the building as of the latest generation of nuclear power plants.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, for example, are continuing their projects with determination.
The United States, after Fukushima have decided to add an unit to their park in the construction of a suspended after the accident at Three Mile Island.
If the German model, focusing on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality has the speech.
The choice of Berlin will result in the increase in the price of electricity, energy dependency aggravated by the increased reliance on imported gas, especially Russia, a jump of CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal.
In a few months, all of these adverse effects are already taking place.
The case of Denmark is to entertain.
European champions of the wind, which accounts for 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas because of the intermittency of the wind; as a result, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Conversely, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an invoice d "electricity 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial plant on the national territory, French companies benefit from "the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Therefore, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear would result in a substantial increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory fine words on the redevelopment of our country and the defence of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French are unwilling to pay, especially as they are not opposed in principle to this energy, the polls show.
The energy policy of our country helped build an industrial sector of 125 000 direct jobs and 410 000 jobs.
Export oriented, it results in a galaxy of specialised SMEs on international markets and makes them very creative jobs that cannot be relocated.
If France were to decide to phase out nuclear power, it would be sacrificing many of these SMEs by reducing to nothing the EUR 6 billion annual export French d "nuclear equipment and services.
What would an electrician PRT designed to operate sixty years while the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, we must admit that there is no source of electricity production "miracle, any more than there is of evil.
The development of Areva solutions low-carbon CO2, nuclear and renewable, testifies to the complementarity of sources of energy.
For the nuclear, maintain the highest level of security is an absolute imperative.
In France we have a security control uncompromising and transparent on existing plants as on the Flamanville site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited the same obsession with security.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has suffered three serious accidents.
One, Three Mile Island, intervened in conditions of normal operation; he remained without a human and environmental.
In Chernobyl, the reactor design and unforgivable human error caused the tragedy.
Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw the lessons of this accident, as it did for the two previous ones.
Fruit of this approach and cooperation between security authorities, operators and manufacturers French and German, the PRT presents a design make it capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is regarded by all the electricians who want to build a powerhouse, the judgment of its construction at Flamanville site would be a magnificent gift to competitors of Areva and EDF leaving the way open for leadership in the development of nuclear power.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek out the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow the emotion, dogmas and the partisan tactics dominate a debate as instrumental to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration is a chance for the economy?
Immigration policy conducted under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles -engorgement police, judicial and administrative subject to the policy of the figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "countries of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is administrative harassment for foreign students who was in the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of 23 May) proclaiming that France "has no need of foreign talent, masons and restaurant servers."
But it is rarely analysed in economic terms.
Is that there is on this subject a fairly broad consensus between left and right.
On the right, the tone was given by Jacques Chirac who said in 1976 that "900000 unemployed people should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million migrant workers," and to the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the poverty in the world in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared to the left and right.
For the two sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that we only be prepared to grant towards immigrants.
In its programme, François Hollande is limited to the trivial, indicating that the co-development will solve our problem "migration."
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be charged electorally; but it is economically very costly.
As the recall economists Ian Goldin, Geoffrey Cameron in a recent book synthesizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, pp. 352), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration on economic growth, salaries and employment in the countries that receive immigrants.
Restrict immigration anemia growth and employment.
The fears of the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they may be a substitute for national workers, particularly the low-skilled, putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes to domestic wage earners, for most of the trades in areas of shortage of employment.
Immigrants low-skilled work in areas that do not attract national employees, and the most qualified in dynamic in which training is not following the availability of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way as a surgeon will be difficult to work in a country that suffers a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants are that the arrival of immigrants have a positive effect on wages and employment of national.
Giovanni Peri has calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows resulting in an increase between 0.6% and 0.9% in real wages in the long term.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and to economic growth (high proportion of immigrants naturalized among the Nobel Prize American; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors of social systems, an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labor Organization estimates that, for example, in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue minus expenses) of EUR 150000 to public budgets on average over the whole of his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to, at the beginning of the mandate, the points of growth "with missing teeth."
The teeth, used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, indeed suggests European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a rather fragile.
The European continent should remember him that, having invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, has experienced in the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, of totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulags, but also in Spain Franco, Salazar in Portugal, the Colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be sufficient, for democracy triomphât definitively of its enemies, to exercise the vote, and to exercise in the most direct manner.
We know, since the "Little Napoleon," that this was a facility of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and may even be "instrument of oppression" as used the philosopher Etienne Republican Vacherot.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation of powers and control, education, of the Enlightenment, of solidarity, economic and social justice.
The crisis in Europe that we live in is an economic crisis, but it is just as important and a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinodie of the Greek referendum will have had in this regard value of double revealing: that of the need for a return of policy, but also the sense of his troubling inability, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be exceeded.
The truth is that the front lines of combat democratic are today displaced, and that, for many, the Republicans are more in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain to demand a succession of national referendums, organized an ad hoc manner and in a disorganised manner.
A blank cheque to the absolute monarch or an European jumping feet into the empty nationalist withdrawal: what choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want to all but a year, common, as of right, calm and continuous, choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - cannot be more where l "stop list - because there is a crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe which pander to the dictates of the markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe who is humiliated on the international stage.
There are concerns about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe who slowly loses its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the piloting of the European project.
Because that is all that Europeans can reduce the weight of their debts, break free markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The crisis exit will involve decisions at European level which cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After long fought this proposal of Socialists and of Jacques Delors, everyone is asking for European economic government.
.
But the think without political integration and more democratic, and seen as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We have a new stage of European integration.
For the Republic in France, it was necessary to "do" of Republicans.
The Revolution in interests could not be sufficient.
This lesson remains valid.
We must build a more integrated Europe economically.
This can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe on the political front, a genuine popular sovereignty.
For Europe, of Europeans.
Smart cards "no touch" spreading
The global smart card opens Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, in a climate optimistic.
The year 2011 is expected to complete on a 11% increase in global sales of smart cards (bank card, with telephone SIM card...), to more than 6 billion units, according to the Eurosmart.
The largest technology without contact which allows for the payment of public transport or resolve its purchases as simply a card for a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless smart cards should be sold across the world, up from 320 million a year earlier.
Their share should increase further in 2012 (580 million units expected) and represent almost 10% of the global market for smart card (6.925 million cards).
Long the world of the Asia-Pacific region, Europe is gaining ground for the payment without contact.
Some 26 million bank cards Visa are already equipped with this functionality and 75.000 payment terminals.
In France, the beginnings are more modest: 400.000 Visa contactless cards have been deployed.
But large surfaces are working extra hard.
Carrefour has issued this year and 2.5 million cards Pass MasterCard without contact.
To go up a gear, now that the banks and their customers.
"Two major French institutions are committed to disseminate to the future systematically to their clients of bank cards equipped for the without contact," Gérard Nébouy, Director General Visa Europe France.
The banks are testing the payment by mobile
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Little devices today are equipped with technology NFC (Near Field Communication) essential to complete transactions.
"They have fallen behind."
"But they should finally have a real growth next year."
"We are building on the sale of 80 to 120 million units in 2012 in the world," says Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But banks take the lead.
Crédit Agricole yesterday announced the launch of a test from December to June next to Caen.
The iPhone of some 200 clients and collaborators will be equipped with a carrying case authorizing payment without contact.
The PCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the General Society, too, said yesterday prepare the placing on the market of an offer to its customers to pay without contact with their mobile.
Sahara in Nigeria, the terrorist front extends
Paris is concerned about the links between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and Boko Haram sect.
