Axis terrorist
Analysis of calls made to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two issues of particular interest to investigators: one leads to a man who has spent in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, cradle of Boko Haram and the other to a man who is close to Aqmi and the sect.
"It is a step forward but it certainly expect more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it is possible."
"We know for years that the sect has been receiving financial support and intellectual external and that it is becoming more active," tempers Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months these "support" had been increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or in their operating procedures, which involve the use of suicide bombers or explosives increasingly complex and of the same material as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has therefore put pressure on Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of illuminated little of interest.
A rapid success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and UQU09Z10L019 fundamentalist Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - Hausa means "Western education is a sin" - calls for the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association has a rapid success.
It is politicizing and requires strict adherence to Sharia law while its activists committed the fight against the central government of Libya.
These are intended first churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, militants from Boko Haram were particularly active, multiplying attacks against police stations.
The reaction of Abuja is, as usual, without nuances.
The army invests the city, there are 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested living, was killed in prison.
Therefore the sect will radicalise and leave its fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, it claims an attack which killed 80 people in Jos, and another in Abuja.
In June, it is still in Abuja that Boko Haram is to secure the police in a suicide attack, its first.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist in Africa that would sail from Mauritania to Somalia and Nigeria is now all security specialists.
While Aqmi invested Mali and Niger, that the Somalis al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram appears as a new threat at the heart of the continent.
Last week, in an interview in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and said he was ready "to share all information."
The world according to the Republican candidates to the Presidency
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry vying to oversimplification and ignorance.
An America weakened by the crisis can manage a complex world with simple ideas, even simplistic?
To listen to the Republican presidential candidates, voters may believe.
In recent days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and the other a thundering declarations and shortcuts in foreign policy, traditionally a Republican.
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, slogans - often not supported - abound.
Mitt Romney, best placed in the race for the appointment of the "Grand Old Party," has threatened to drag the Chinese before the WTO and the need to question "for manipulation of their currency," a theme in an America exasperated by the migration of whole swathes of its industry to Asia.
Too bad if it must involve the calling of a trade war, "he said.
Jon Huntsman, former Ambassador to China of Obama and only candidate to have a vision of foreign policy, has failed to strangle an attitude that "dismay" the emotions.
He called for a tough but constructive dialogue with Beijing (the current position of Obama).
But Huntsman, who sits in the depths of the surveys, remains inaudible.
The image of Reagan
Romney has also promised military strikes on Iran if sanctions fail to stop its nuclear program.
"If I am elected, I will leave Iran," he off. "
"If Obama is re-elected, they will have the bomb."
He also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing in its obligations to this partner.
The entrepreneur Herman Cain, second candidate best placed, a lack of embarrassing files.
Recently, he called to address the threat of Chinese military because Beijing "is trying to develop a nuclear capability" - apparently ignoring the fact that China holds the military since 1964.
The Texas governor Rick Perry, which supports Israel and wants to strikes against Iran, is prepared to engage the American army in Mexico against the drug cartels.
The use of torture against suspected terrorists, prohibited by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry, and the candidate Michele Bachmann.
It is far from the 2008 Republican candidate, John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
Opponents of the current president retorted that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They recall that Obama himself was a fan and that he had to put water in its wine Anti-Terrorism Initiative.
They rightly stress the failure of its dialogue with Iran naive, on the departure too rushed "boys" of Iraq, on his procrastination in Libya, and a sticky label of low.
But the attack is not so easy.
The judge rather positive assessment of national security for Obama, who has eliminated Bin Laden.
Since Iraq, it is wary of military interventions that lead to inertia.
And, on the grounds that it is economically rebuild America to resurrect his leadership, Obama appears more fair.
The Nord Stream, new door / Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, connecting Western Europe directly to Russia to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, came into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event.
More than 500 guests including four Heads of State and Government have participated, last Tuesday, on the banks of the Baltic, between orchestra and buffet end, at the opening of the Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects directly, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, the German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned the wheel of the valve commander the entry of Russian gas in the network there.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas additional will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first tube of 1 224 km linking the St Petersburg region in the Land of Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second tube must be completed by the end of 2012, to issue a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, the equivalent of any French consumption.
And there is already talk the opportunity to build a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time of this enormous site has the air of victory.
The project had been strongly opposed by Poland and the Baltic countries.
Nord Stream will allow us to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding land by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some of their power: it makes it more difficult for them to influence Russia by threatening to deny it access to European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet Pact," in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for Poland, in 1939.
That is, if the topic is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this project Russian, earned greater security of supply.
But it is the price of a weakening of the Europe of energy, since the project has created a gap between people of Eastern and Western.
Russia has been able, in five years ago, to its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, strongly gas consumers, and whose deposits are in decline.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Fillon opening this pipeline, demonstrating how close the major gas contracts are also political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles posted by the leaders of Gazprom, present in number to Lubmin, to the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The submarine is steel wrapped with concrete to protect against the anchors of vessels.
It is based on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
For the building, it was necessary to avoid areas of mines from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for the company Nord Stream.
It took the measures to protect the flora and fauna.
The tube is a long snake to heavy metal, such as 242 Eiffel Towers, that nothing stops along its entire length: neither valve, or station maintenance.
A platform of control was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project have renounced while the Swedes were unwilling to see a Crown corporation Russian permanently off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas content in the pipeline is therefore in the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by manufacturers who have provided the welds for a leak every 100 000 years.
Monitoring the condition of the pipeline is provided by a robot submarine, dragged by a ship, for external monitoring, as well as a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
Of the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, large one metre in diameter, and it is driven by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 metres, the second book detailed information on the potential distortions of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate fifty years without the slightest compensation.
The gas flow is simply provided by the pressure.
It is 200 bar at the outset, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which keeps 51% of the shares.
Have joined the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), and the Dutch Gasunie and French GDF Suez group (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, named Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable.
Gazprom has then leased to the company, for twenty years, all of the gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the quantity of gas really transported," says Jens Müller.
The funding of the construction of the pipeline was 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment amounted to 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are safe to return to their costs, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The pipeline is emerging from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted pine.
Valves, high of 4.5 metres, form the exit door of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature, and the specific characteristics of the gas that is, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas for each hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Boots, a mark.
It created a couple of years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has an air of adventures, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine is easily recognizable, with its coverage, its rectangular black elastic, the leaves of a colour off-white, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine as we know it today... Was born in 1997.
The Italian company simple simple, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook design but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, the launch of the new product.
The book is based on a former technical production, the mole skin (skin of Townsend) which means a cotton varnish used to cover benches for example.
This type of book was very popular writers and travellers.
"New updated version of an old and forgotten, who was an icon of the avant-garde artists, until the twentieth century," says Maria Sebregondi, now responsible for the mark in modo simple.
The success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million coins.
It is far from the production version of the early years, where only 3 000 books were designed.
New exceeds the Italian borders and exports in 70 countries, of France to the United States.
Difficult to establish a composite drawing of the purchaser, because the notebook seduced both the make entrepreneurs "that the student and professionals.
The image of Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and grown.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its infancy, has almost 100 today and has since 2008 of two offices; one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its books in bookstores, the small shops downtown and has been able to impose its identity.
"We have followed the spirit of the times and this need new writing, despite the growth of e-mails," says Maria Sebregondi.
This signature cultural accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched a "Detour" where architects or artists expose their own book.
In August, it has also launched a leopard, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this will be cultural, Moleskine managed to diversify products: bags, agenda, pens, covers computer ... The mark takes on a wide range of media.
A success that has made envious: in the fall of 2006, simple simple was bought by the investment funds SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why the unemployment rate for disabled workers is so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are in search of work.
The 15th week for the employment of the disabled opens today.
Despite a proactive policy put in place in 2005, the unemployment rate of people with disabilities is still two times higher than the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the whole population.
Discouraging?
"No," said Eric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt, the association which organises the week for the employment of disabled. "
"The progress made since fifteen are considerable."
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times."
"It is still a great deal to do."
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, many barriers still exist prior to employment.
They are older: 37% are over 50 years (17% on average).
They have a level of qualification: 80% have not tray and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10 000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, against 38% on average.
In short, as many criteria that are making the return to employment, and that is the crux of the problem, "according to Christian Grapin, Director General of Springboard, an association established in 1992 to help companies to recruit workers with disabilities.
So much for the brakes objectives.
The rest unsaid, attitudes are changing that, yes, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre Precinct indicated that managers surveyed have "low levels of knowledge of disability," with a "over-representation of people in wheelchairs, deficient mental or intellectual."
Outcome, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the objective of employment of 6% of workers with disabilities, set in a law of... 1987.
The latest figures available, dating from 2008, point to a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre White, Director General of the;, the agency responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not comply with the law.
The evidence: the number of institutions "taxed," just as the amounts paid, declined between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The Act of 2005, which increased contributions, has created a strong pressure on companies," explains Pierre White. "
"But this improvement also reflects a real gesture of awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of 20 to 49 employees employ workers with disabilities, against 82% of businesses in 100 to 199 employees.
